,Not Recommended,510510,30347690,Posted: 5 March,all,Andariel Halo,"Having skipped a few years from WWE 13 to WWE 2k16, i was blown away by 16 and loved it and found lots to do.  I was extremely anxious for WWE 2k17, expecting it to be an augment for 2k16, something like what WWF No Mercy was over WWF Wrestlemania 2000.The end result is immensely dissatisfying, though.  The graphics look exactly the same to me, though there may be some improvements.  Something about the way the flesh and colors look makes them all look flat and plastic.  The sort of dis-realism of the wrestlers and their expressions from 2k16 were not at all addressed here.  The game modes are all the same from 2k16, with backstage brawling and crowd brawling finally added in, but segregated so that you can't go backstage during the course of a tables match or hell in a cell match, but only if you pick Backstage Brawl.The roster list is the same ugly mess that came with 2k16.  Current superstars are mixed in with former superstars and superstar variants, seemingly without care.  Certain superstars who would have been highly publicized for inclusion (or were highly publicized for previous years) or made something unlockable or part of a ""Legends"" pack are just there, included in the list as if they were Aidan English or Zack Ryder, with no special labeling or being included in a separate list.The DLC for new superstars is also massively underwhelming, charging 9-10 dollars for about 7 superstars total, while not bothering to add people like the current NXT champion Bobby Roode.Ultimately what killed this game for me was the lack of attention or care to details.  Simple things that could have added a bit of zest to the experience.  WWE 2k16 had this for me in the form of the wrestler taunts; certain wrestlers' taunts had them speaking out loud.The nature of NXT now is such that it has a highly devoted, energetic fanbase, and the experience of having crowds sing along with Nakamura or Bobby Roode's entrance music can be just as awesome as a match itself.  As more NXT favorites come to the main roster (like Kevin Owens, Samoa Joe, Bayley, Charlotte Flair), their fans stick with them and bring their unique reactions and chants with them.WWE 2k17 has nothing at all like that.  The crowd is dead as any other WWE game, with the exact same monotonous crowd noise triggered at the same points of an entrance.  No one sings along to Shinsuke Nakamura's music.  There are no competing chants, no half-boos and half-cheers for the likes of John Cena or AJ Styles.  No one chants ""Joe's gonna kill you"" or ""Asuka's gonna kill you"" at the start of a Samoa Joe or Asuka match.  A superstar labelled a heel is flatly booed with generic audience boos, a face is flatly cheered with generic cheers.And the multiplayer for PC is essentially DOA.  It's exactly the same double-blind matchmaking system from WWE 2k16, where you can be waiting for hours for a matchup that will never happen while being forced to ""practice"" wrestle against the computer in an empty arena.Ultimately this game reeks of mediocrity, being just another cash-grab entry in a franchise that has to put out a new game yearly.  Sometimes the cycle gets broken with a whole new game (recently like WWE 12 over the Smackdown vs Raw series), but this latest entry is stuck in the middle, being little more than some tiny changes and added features over the previous entries.For a first-time buy, or for someone who hasn't played since Smackdown vs Raw, this would be an amazing WWE game, but if you've played WWE 2k16, this is more of the same, safe and predictable."
