,Recommended,510510,33316005,Posted: 6 July,all,Officer Cum Shot,"I'm going to try and make this an in depth review, in order to help others who are considering this game in the future.I have been waiting for this game to come on sale for quite the time now, because I had this on last gen, and like the most of us: I didn't want to pay the full price. I would constantly check Geetwoaye(tried to blur it out) but there wasn't any sort of deal. So when I finally saw it on the Steam Summer Sale, I was lucky enough to have enough in my account to buy the game.I was conflicted for the most part because I saw a lot of negative reviews, but I played 2k16 on PC as well and didn't find many problems. I decided to get the deluxe edition for 23 I believe(could have been 24) instead of the game because a few dollars more to get ALL the DLC is clearly worth it than spending the $75.In terms of the gameplay:I thought the gameplay was a lot better than 2k16. I saw gameplay on 2k15 for PC but I have no intention of buying it because 2k17 has managed to keep me entertained. There are plenty of different combinations to execute different moves and I thought it was improved and loved having more moves being added. I use a controller and the one thing I like and dislike at the same time is choosing who you go after in a match. Ex) Triple threat and having to hit R3 to change between opponents. It can be a hassle but I see why it was implemented from bugs in 2k16. There are still bugs and times when the move doesn't hit and you fall looking like an idiot but it's far less buggy than 16's. I can run the game at 45-55 FPS depending on the match, but I noticed I get the most lag from 6 man matches. It's bearable but playing an entire match at 30-40 FPS at best can be a little frustrating for many at times.PS: Love the new MITB feature and title match minigame.The announcers are Supeeeeer annoying. You get used to their catchphrases and sayings and everything is the same. I remember a lot of the phrases from 2k16 too(probably a copy/paste from 2k16 to '17)I like the new promo system, and think it's pretty neat and upgraded from 2k16's backstage promo.In terms of Graphics:If you don't have a good computer, you're probably going to have a hard time running this. Granted I can run it smoothly for the most part, all of the negative comments are probably coming from those who's computers can't run it etc. etc. There is random frame loss sometimes like when there's a double camera from being too far apart or sometimes outside the ring but it's manageable for the most part.I always enjoy the rosters. I hope the DLC would cover more or that they could release updates for updated attires, outdated entrances etc. but 2k can get a little lazy(super lazy). Considering the PC version is released many months later, you would figure that you would get A LOT more out of it than the console versions. I miss the Custom Music option from 2k15 I think (could be wrong,whoops) but everyone has the option to mod when it's released.In terms of the Universe Mode:I was iffy on this. I was used to the last few versions, but change isn't always a bad thing. I think the MITB cash in is 1 step too complicated, but isn't the worst of all cases.In terms of MyCareer Mode:I think it's a huge improvement from 2k16. I love love love the option to get extra VC from T-shirt Sales. It's an incentive to change your attire up but I don't like how you have to change it every 1-2 game weeks before your sales drop tremendously( I'm in the 22k VC per week and usually drops 1000 a week, but when I was in the 10k VC area it would drop by a few thousand).I feel that moving up the ranks is a slower process than 2k16 was. I usually move up every month, maybe 2 times per month if I am lucky. Mind you I am putting on 4-5 start matches every time, sometimes 3 if I am lazy. The authority challenges can be super ridiculous, like putting on a 5 star match and losing your title, or something I found impossible, winning by dq(harder than it seems). I wish there was an option to turn off the show logo because after hearing the into for shows around 4-5 times it starts to get pretty annoying. I don't mind the whole (buy a moveset feature), but some of them aren't even worth buying, but they suckered me in because I'm one of those people who will buy all of the VC items whether I will use it or not. It also sucks that there is no voiceover for when you are doing promo's, and sometimes if you skip the promo when you're speaking(hitting a or start for me-xbox controller), you still have to sit through and watch your character mumble words in silence.Overall, I do RECOMMEND this game, but you are going to need a good PC to run it. Like I stated in the beginning, if you have an average or small-tier computer, don't expect to get far. This game is a step up from 2k16 but the price is what gets me. The only way I saw this game being profitable on PC is if people bought it while it was on sale. We have to wait many months after it's released on console to get it on PC, and there's no incentive for the wait. Last year, 2k16 came with all DLC and this year it was seperate. Sticking with the whole all in one combo could have boosted the sales in this scenario. I mean there's nothing extra, and practically are getting the same thing in console, just have to wait longer. Not complaining, but I don't think it helps 2k.On a side note: It sucks for anyone who bought the game only and expected the DLC to be cheaper, because I noticed a lot of complaints during the summer sale that the game and Deluxe edition was on sale, but DLC's were all full price. That also doesn't help 2k because you're encouraging people NOT to buy it right away. If the right optimizations were made, I can see this game being suitable for more people.2k is slowly progressing with their games, but should be going at a faster route. The market for profit SHOULD be for PC, but instead they're letting many people down. I can still play through it, because I'm a fan of the game series, and actually love playing the games: but they need to stop being lazy and get their act together.Online matches are a hit or miss, depending on location,location,location. I once faced a guy and won 2-0 from Asia. Super laggy, but I was able to time his reversals perfectly. The best way to describe it was a slow motion match.Again, most comments that are negative are probably coming from those who CANNOT run it. I can run it, and the only problem I have is slight lag during 6 man matches. No crashes, game save corruptions etc.Overall Rating:8.0 out of 10I've been playing these games since the early Ps2 versions of Here comes the Pain! and believe their games will improve over time. They are slowly improving, but I still believe they can do a lot more in a year if they actually tried more. Instead of going above and beyond it seems they're doing the bear minimum just to get the game released. So much wasted potential, but because I've been playing for so long I can only support and hope for the best(and a lot of miracles).I recommend you get this when it is on sale, because unlike the console versions I don't believe it's worth the price. I mean 2k15 and 16 are still $50 on Steam, with it going on sale once or twice a year. I also recommend getting the deluxe edition when it is on sale, for the obvious reason of it being cheaper."
