,Not Recommended,510510,31656104,Posted: 9 May,all,Ectopilot,"This is a review intended for people considering buying the game. I'm not trying to change or challenge the opinion of anyone who already owns it.TL;DR:Worth it? Unless you're just buying for career mode. On sale, definitely. See my hours.With Friends: GreatUniverse/General Manager Mode: GoodExhibition: Good. Typical. Decent amount of wrestlers although many are DLC.Career Mode: AtrociousUniverse (formerly General Manager Mode) is pretty fun if you enjoy making up scenarios or just simulating and seeing how far everyone gets in the rankings when left alone. I've ended up with Christian being the Heavyweight and US champion for 83 weeks.The Career mode, however, is the worst I've ever seen in a WWE game. Hell, Raw 2 for the Xbox back in 2003 had a much better career mode. There's absolutely no backstory - a little would be nice, but not so much to make it a completely linear story like some of the SvR games. About the only ""drama"" - you could say - that can happen are rivalries. I'll touch on this God-awful feature in a bit. The popularity system also feels like a punishment rather than a challenge - it doesn't matter if you win every single match for six months (I have), if your popularity isn't sky-high you'll never go up a single rank. I've never once been higher than rank 3 for any championship.The ranks are almost arbitrary. I've seen wrestlers with their overall in the 70s - like Callisto - shoot up to #2 or even #1 contender for the Heavyweight championship while 90s overall wrestlers like Taker maintain the same rank for months. The only (or at least most efficient in my experience) way to climb the ranks is to - as I've mentioned - keep your popularity up which is entirely separate from whether you win or lose, and to 'win' rivalries...Rivalries is this game are terrible compared to almost any other WWF/E game I've ever played in nearly twenty years. Basically, you find someone higher on the rankings than you (but not too high or you'll never get a match with them), trash-talk them or interfere in their match enough that they get♥♥♥♥♥♥♥♥at you and you're locked in a rivalry. There is then a ""rivalry point"" system which dictates who ""wins"" the rivalry. Again, it's almost arbitrary, you can beat your rival three times but if they get you with a steel chair as you walk out to fight Daniel Bryan for the sixth week in a row - they'll win the rivalry. Again, there's no drama or even cutscenes related to this - simply a menu that lists who your current rival is. Rivalries tend to go one of two ways:1) You, for some reason, never face your rival. They win the rivalry by default, even if no-one has any rivalry points.2) You face your rival twice a week (Smackdown or Raw, plus Main Event) for a month, then at the pay-per-vier, and maybe go up one rank. There are 10 total, rank 1 being #1 contender.I could write a thesis paper on how much I dislike the Career mode, but for the sake of what little sanity I retain after so much time spent trying to decipher head from♥♥♥♥♥on this mode, I'll cut it here."
