,Recommended,510510,30001437,Posted: 17 February,all,Homeschool Math Class,"As someone who's played nearly all the WWE games since 2002's ""Shut Your Mouth"", I can say that this is definitely one of the better games of the series, and definitely a step up from 2K's other wrestling endeavours.To begin, I get very few performance issues on any game I play, so that means 2K17 is no different. In 25 hours of play, the game has crashed once, and I occasionally get some FPS stutter, but other than that, and the other random glitches you get in a 2K wrestling game, I didn't have any issues in that department.Ever since I started playing wrestling games, I've always played them for the story mode. In Shut Your Mouth and Here Comes the Pain, it was the brilliant Season mode, in 2011 it was the Road to Wrestlemanias, and in 2K's next-gen videogames, it's MyCareer, their vision for the player to be able to recreate what it's like for a WWE superstar to rise up from humble beginnings and become a main eventer, all while relatively keeping kayfabe in check. MyCareer has, for the most part, been nearly exclusively what I've played in 2K's games. In 2015, it was a barebones excuse of a broken system that occasionally produced interesting feuds every ten hours. In 2016, it fixed many of those problems, although these ""fixes"" included 8 redudant matches followed by 1 semi-important match to a feud that was destined to go nowhere, along with title systems that didn't work. In 2K17, these problems are fixed. Not only do you have variety in how feuds start, end, and their length, but you can now challenge for titles much earlier, have much more control over what happens, and a re-balancing of attributes and difficulty makes these matches a genuine challenge while still being close enough and interesting enough to be riveting. You feel a genuine character progression with your CAW, through promos, championship wins, and where his spot on the card happens to land every week. Now, only occasionally do the eight matches between PPVs feel tedious, unlike 2K16, where they almost always did.My primary complaints lie in the fact that the customization suite doesn't seem to be as detailed as last years, at least for CAWs. Overall, though, there does seem to be more content within the game, including an absolutely massive roster and many different arenas. With that being said, DLC that was free last year will cost you $30 this year, as will some basic features that were available last year. The only reason I can look over this is because I think all the other items in the Season Pass are definitely worth $30, and as an avid fan of WWE, I'm willing to pay that much money for the product. Considering that it was FREE last year, however, does make me slightly sour.Considering all my experiences I've had in the 25 hours I've played so far, I'd recommend a buy. But try your best to make sure you can also buy the season pass, too. If you don't, you miss out on very valuable roster members, including Eddie Guerrero, Tye Dillinger, and the Club, along with basic functions such as editing the stats of pre-existing wrestlers. If you can get over that small detail and have enough money to spend on this game, the combination of MyCareer and a fun wrestling sim will be enough to hold you over for quite a while."
