,Not Recommended,510510,30654648,Posted: 21 March,all,ADZE,"It feels a bit sparse, and in my eyes it doesn't quite compare to some of the earlier games in the series. It's as though more effort went into the earlier games. I haven't played many of the WWE games in years, in fact the last one I actually owned was WWE SvR 2009. Therefore with an 8 year gap between games, the difference in quality is striking, whether this is due to the series being taken over by 2K or just a general lack of creativity among the creators. It feels very uninspired and unfinished. I understand that these guys are expected to put out a new game every year, but still.The graphics are better than 2009 etc, but that's to be expected and not something that I focus on much. It does make my PC lag pretty badly, but with a crappy little box like mine, that's more my fault than theirs.The MyCareer mode feels outright repetitive with the illusion of challenges thrown in to try and spice up the repetitive slog of match after match after match. It also bugs me that you go straight from the training facility to WWE RAW. In my second week I was put up against Brock Lesnar. There's no sense of build-up, aside from the paper-thin Championship rankings, etc. I get that this is how it's been for years now, but in previous years the Career mode had actual storylines with rivalries and choice-based branching paths. This version doesn't even have voice acting besides the commentators, the ringside announcers, and A-Train near the start. This is how it was in WWE 2005, 12 years ago! And even then, WWE 2005 had actual storylines. It feels like 2K decided to focus more on implementing larger rosters and ""sharp, fluid gameplay"" rather than making things actually entertaining.It's very jarring to have your match interrupted with an Instant Replay whenever you do something big. It's a great example of putting realism before player enjoyment. I just did the move! I know how it works! I don't need to have the pace of the match brought to a screeching halt to see it 3 more times. Save it for the post-match highlights if you need to put it somewhere. I know I can skip it, but it still throws me off, because *it doesn't happen every time you do your finisher*. You can't be prepared for it! At least you can choose to turn settings like these off.The AI is choppy at times. Every now and again you'll get thrown to the floor and your opponent will instead step out onto the apron and throw punches at thin air. Or else your teammates/opponents will get out of te ring and not try to climb back in before the 10-count. I won't mention the glitches though. Those have been around for ages and they're not getting fixed any time soon.One thing though - and I'm not sure if I messed up or if something's actually wrong, but in MyCareer mode, my created superstar's entrance music doesn't play despite me making 110% sure that it does. The post-match music works perfectly though. What gives?Also - and this is something I've seen tons of other people complain about - the game keeps crashing! I have to constantly hold thumbs that the game won't conk out when I'm in the middle of doing something important. Yesterday I spent 20+ minutes tweaking my created superstar's moveset when the game crashed out of nowhere and I lost all my progress. Seriously, there's like a 50% chance that if I try to edit my character it'll crash. And then I need to wait 5 minutes for the damn thing to boot up again (if I don't give up and play something else for a while) and run the risk of it just crashing again. The PC version has been out for nearly two months! Surely this is something that could (and should) have been fixed early on? I'd be so much happier if I could just play the damn thing. Please just fix the crashing issue and I can deal with the rest. Are we just on our own from now on? This stuff is game-breaking. People are spending serious money on a game that only works when it feels like it.It also bugs me that I can't skip cutscenes. I'm so sick of watching the RAW and SmackDown intro sequences.I do like how they can read out my full name though :P ""From Cape Town, South Africa... Adam McKay!"" I never get tired of that. I also like the roster, with the potential to buy a ton of bonus superstars (and for in-game currency too, thank god!)As I mentioned before, this game feels unfinished, making me wonder if I should have bought one of the earlier games instead. Considering that you don't really get your money's worth, I probably wouldn't recommend it to a friend. There's just so much missing from previous years that were awesome! Finisher creators, Storyline creators, Career storylines, actual voice acting! I get that the game is already 40+ GB as it is, but making it seem less sparse would definitely make people enjoy it more. As it is, I feel silly for paying so much for something with not very much to offer. I feel as though I'm lumbered with it, rather than being the proud owner of my first WWE game in 8 years.It's not fun."
