76561198081998310,Not Recommended,510510,29793055,Posted: 8 February,all,DoubleCee33,"As a casual wrestling gamer I honestly haven't noticed that much of a change from the previous game to this one, yeah sure the roster has been updated and there are a couple of more noticeable features that the previous release didn't have, however if you're asking me whether you can justify almost 80 Australian dollars on this game I honestly don't know if I could give you a definitive yes.Career mode still feels like a bit of an endless grind, they certainly made improvements from the previous game in relation to the career mode but it still nowhere near as good as you find in other sports games such is NBA 2K17 and now FIFA 17.Customisation wise I actually feel like they've gone backwards, when creating a custom superstar you can no longer select from premade faces, it's now entirely up to you to supply any kind of individuality to your CAW, the pre-selected attire is still restrictive to say the least, the one thing I will give about the player customisation is the hair you can assign to your custom superstar finally looks halfway to being realistic but is still nowhere near acceptable for a 5 star game.From a mechanics point of view the game still feels laggy, it still tends to glitch out especially when playing a game involving more than two Superstars, the Royal Rumble mode is near unplayable especially when the ring is filling up.DLC wise I think they have done the best they could, the NXT addition was a nice improvement to the game, many people wanted Shinsuke Nakamura added to the game and we finally got it.Overall I would give this game a 7 out of 10, the argument could be made that it's better and more enjoyable than WWE 2K16 and the new features would to some people merit spending the money to upgrade to the new version, however I still believe that it is nowhere near as good as the old SmackDown vs Raw games used to be.Overall improvements have been made but there is 