,Recommended,510510,34172699,Posted: 11 August,all,LuciditySam,"As much as I enjoy this game and typically turn to this game when I just want to unwind and relax, this game has some glaring flaws.The gameplay itself usually is very good but that's only if you can ignore major issues that arise here and there. Irish whip your target into the turnbuckle and there's a possibility that when you use your running strike that you will just bounce off your opponent like you missed. Outside of table matches, tables will not break if you try to drive your opponent through them due to a patch that broke how tables work. Not only that, but you won't even be able to pick the table back up. The announce tables work perfectly but not the regular tables. Then there's the issues with frame drops and, when using created wrestlers and arenas, the loading times can get very long. This is coming from someone using an i6700k CPU, 16GB of RAM, and a GTX1070. It is a locked 60 frames per second and, on my rig, it is pretty stable in terms of frame rate outside of when someone interrupts your entrance. At that point, it drops down to 30-40.Graphically, the game is tolerable. It's far from realistic-looking but it's not bad in terms of how it looks during gameplay and entrances. The problem is that it's got a lot of low-resolution textures and images for things like tattoos and logos. There are graphical glitches where you get a colored line (like a black line stretching from black fingernails, for example) on created characters at times. They're not too common but they do exist. The hair also does not act like hair; it's basically early PS3-level hair physics.The creation suit is very basic, though. I love creating new characters and entrances; it's very hard in this game to create anyone who is unique that would also be someone that could be a real character. You can create some weird♥♥♥♥♥♥ gorillas,  and stupid things like that but unless you're really good with uploading images, making face-scans, and things like that then you will have one hell of a time creating anyone unique without a mask or a ton of makeup caked on. Creating an entrance can sometimes be fun if you're into that, though my two biggest gripes is you can't use your custom entrance if you're holding a championship belt and the fact that you can't make custom lighting or choose camera angles. The camera angles make it very jarring because the number of hard cuts makes it obvious when the entrance doesn't match up (entering ring from left side, suddenly on ringside on the right in the next scene, for example).Simply put, if you can get this with the Season Pass for $25 or less and you can't wait until 2k18 releases for your platform of choice then definitely get this one. At full price at this point, I'd recommend against it. However, I have to give this a ""Recommended"" as I put hundreds of hours on the PS4 version and decided to rebuy it on PC. Between the bugs, how minimal the improvements from 2k16 are, and the very stripped-down/barebones creation suite? This is definitely a 6/10, maybe a 7/10 if you wanted to be generous. Hopefully 2k18 will be a significant improvement now that the PS3 and XBox 360 will no longer be supported."
